%I A276661 #94 Jun 12 2026 10:29:30
%S A276661 0,1,2,4,7,13,24,44,84,161,309
%N A276661 Least k such that there is a set S in {1, 2, ..., k} with n elements and the property that each of its subsets has a distinct sum.
%C A276661 This sequence is the main entry for the distinct subset sums problem. See also A201052, A005318, A005255.
%C A276661 The Conway-Guy sequence A005318 is an upper bound. Lunnon showed that a(67) < 34808838084768972989 = A005318(67), and Bohman improved the bound to a(67) <= 34808712605260918463.
%C A276661 Lunnon found a(0)-a(8) and J. P. Grossman found a(9).
%C A276661 a(10) > 220, with A201052. - _Fausto A. C. Cariboni_, Apr 06 2021
%C A276661 From _Ven Popov_, Nov 27 2025, edited by _Michael S. Branicky_, Jan 25 2026: (Start)
%C A276661 a(12) <= 1157 < 1164 = A005318(12), since {1157, 1152, 1149, 1147, 1145, 1141, 1130, 1108, 1069, 993, 845, 554} is a potential optimal solution.
%C A276661 a(13) <= 2249 < 2284 = A005318(13), since {2249, 2243, 2240, 2237, 2230, 2225, 2220, 2197, 2154, 2078, 1931, 1637, 1077} is a potential optimal solution. (End)
%C A276661 If S is a solution for a(n), then {1} U 2*S is a solution for a(n+1). - _Touch Sungkawichai_, Jan 24 2026
%C A276661 From _Michael S. Branicky_, Jan 24 2026 (Start):
%C A276661 Using the construction for the distinct subset sum Conway-Guy sets S_i [Bohman, Sec. 2]:
%C A276661 a(11) <= A005318(11) = 594, as evidenced by {285, 433, 510, 550, 570, 581, 587, 590, 592, 593, 594}.
%C A276661 See a-file for the Conway-Guy bounds and sets S_n for n = 1..100. (End)
%D A276661 J. H. Conway and R. K. Guy, Solution of a problem of P. Erdos, Colloq. Math. 20 (1969), p. 307.
%D A276661 R. K. Guy, Unsolved Problems in Number Theory, Section C8.
%H A276661 Iskander Aliev, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00454-008-9059-9">Siegel's lemma and sum-distinct sets</a>, Discrete Comput. Geom. 39 (2008), 59-66; arXiv:<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0503115">math/0503115</a> [math.NT], 2005.
